#Text=Lottie Kimbrough
#Text=Lottie Kimbrough ( born 1893 [ 3 ] or 1900 ; [ 4 ]
#Text=date of death unknown ) was an American country blues singer , who was also billed as Lottie Beaman ( her married name ) , Lottie Kimborough , and Lena Kimbrough ( among several other names ) .
#Text=She was a large woman and was nicknamed " The Kansas City Butterball " . [ 2 ] [ 5 ]
#Text=Her recording career lasted from 1924 to 1929 .

#Text=The music journalist Burgin Mathews wrote that " Kimbrough 's vocal power , and the unique arrangements of several of her best pieces , rank her as one of the sizable talents of the 1920s blues tradition . " [ 2 ]

column1: #Text=Biography
#Text=Kimbrough was born in either Jonesboro , Arkansas , [ 3 ] or West Bottoms , Kansas City , Missouri , [ 2 ] and had close links with the Kansas City community .
#Text=By 1915 she was using the name Lottie Mitchell , and by 1920 she had married William Beaman . [ 3 ]
#Text=Her music career began in the early 1920s , when she performed in nightclubs and speakeasies in Kansas City . [ 4 ]
#Text=Her career was managed by Winston Holmes , a local musician and music promoter . [ 2 ]
#Text=In 1924 she undertook her first recording session , for Paramount Records , where she was recorded alongside Ma Rainey .
#Text=Her earliest recordings were made with the accompaniment of the twins Milas and Miles Pruitt ( banjo and guitar , respectively ) .
#Text=She was later backed by Jimmy Blythe ( piano ) . [ 2 ]
#Text=In 1925 she shared recording studio space with Papa Charlie Jackson .
#Text=The same year she cut some tracks for Merrit Records , owned by Holmes . [ 4 ]
#Text=Kimbrough recorded and performed using a number of pseudonyms .
#Text=She used her married name , Lottie Beaman , on almost half of her tracks , but for her 1926 recording sessions Holmes suggested that she be renamed Lena Kimbrough .
#Text=He also used a photograph of her more photogenic sister , Estella , for publicity . [ 2 ]
#Text=Kimbrough also appeared billed as Clara Cary and as Mae Moran .

#Text=She further recorded in Richmond , Indiana , and pseudonyms were used for issues by Gennett Records , Champion Records ( which billed her as Lottie Emerson ) , Supertone Records ( as Lottie Brown ) and Superior Records ( as Martha Jackson ) . [ 4 ] [ 6 ]
#Text=Her Gennett sessions produced the tracks " Rolling Log Blues " and " Goin ' Away Blues " , which the music journalist Tony Russell described as having " haunting beauty " . [ 7 ]
#Text=Kimbrough 's brother Sylvester appeared with her in vaudeville , and in 1926 he supplied recording accompaniment for Paul Banks 's Kansas City Trio .
#Text=However , Kimbrough 's musical collaboration with Holmes produced her better-known recordings .
#Text=Holmes supplied yodels and vocalised bird calls and train whistles on " Lost Lover Blues " and " Wayward Girl Blues " ( 1928 ) .
#Text=Miles Pruitt participated in this recording and was a regular partner throughout Kimbrough 's recording and concert career .
#Text=He was featured again when Kimbrough recorded her final session , in November 1929 . [ 2 ]

#Text=" Rolling Log Blues " , one of the songs she wrote , has been recorded by Jo Ann Kelly , Woody Mann , Son House , the Blues Band , Rory Block , Eric Bibb , Maria Muldaur , and Buffy Sainte-Marie . [ 8 ]
#Text=Little is known of her life beyond her recording career . [ 4 ]
#Text=According to records indexed in Ancestry.com , she was born in May 1893 , had son Alex Leroy Mitchell in 1912 , and her granddaughter Alice was born in 1928 .
